* [Trajectory Optimization](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wlkRYMVUZTs): Set of mathematical techniques to find the ideal or desired behaviour  
  * Trying to control the input into the system which yield the desired behaviour   
  * Solves an optimal control problem   
  * Closed-loop solution:  
    * Global method and solution   
    * Always find the solution  
    * More difficult to compute   
    * Action to take at every point of the state space  
    * Primarily used for low dimensional  
  * Open-loop solution   
    * u \= u(t)  
      * Control as a function of time   
    * No info about the system when its off the trajectory   
    * local methods and solution   
    * Less difficult to compute   
    * Used for higher dimensional problems  
* Assumptions  
  * Continuous time (as opposed to discrete)  
  * Single phase  
    * Single start and end point, and continuous in between   
  * Dynamics, objectives and constraints are smooth, consistent, potentially non-linear   
  * No if statements   
* Objective Function: function describing optimal trajectory   
  * Boundary of the trajectory, first and final point)  
    * How good or bad is it to be in a specific start or ending point   
  * Integral Objective function   
    * Quantity along the trajectory  
      * Motor torque   
  * Minimizing over the initial and final time of the trajectory as well as the state along the trajectory and state along the trajectory   
* Transcription   
  * Trajectory optimization problem int constrained parameter optimization problem  
  * Non linear program   
    * Constrained parameter optimization problem   
    * decision variable are real number   
    * Finite dimensional   
    * Algebraic equations  
  * Trajectory optimization problem   
    * Decision variable are vector function   
    * Infinite dimensional   
    * Differential equations  
  * How to discretize problem  
    * Indirect Method   
      * Optimize then discretize  
      * More accurate   
      * Harder to pose and solve  
    * Direct Method   
      * Discretize then optimize  
      * Less accurate  
      * Easier to pose and solve   
  *  The actual discretization done via   
    * Shooting Methods   
      * runga-kutta  
      * Based on simulation  
      * Better for problems with simple control and no path constraints  
    * Collocation Methods   
      * The idea is to choose a finite-dimensional space of candidate solutions and a number of points in the domain (called *collocation points*), and to select that solution which satisfies the given equation at the collocation points.  
      * Based on function approximation   
        * Implicit integrator   
      * Better for problems with complicated control and or path constraints  
  *  How to increase or improve the accuracy of the methods  
    * Blending of these two is usually done  
    * H-methods  
      * Low order method   
      * Increase the number of trajectory segments   
      * Take more time steps of the same order methods  
      * Converge by increasing the number of segments  
    * p-methods    
      * High order methods   
      * Increase the accuracy of the methods  
      * Converge by increasing method order   
  * Direct Transcriptions   
    * Continuous time and functions and convert to discrete set of real numbers   
    * Number of grid points   
    * State and control as set of values at those grid points  
  * Trapezoidal Calocation   
    * Assumption for linear behaviour   
* Initializing NLP   
  * Initial solution guess  
    * Neglect dynamics   
    * Replace difficult objective with and easy one   
    * Remove difficult constraints   
    * Use small number of grid points  
* Interpolation   
  * Spline   
    * Sequence of polynomials   
    * Order of the state spline is generally of a higher order then the control spline  
* Solution Accuracy   
  * Collocation constraints   
  * Error   
    * Defect between system dynamics differentiating the solution   
    * And system dynamics by evaluating the dynamics function at each point   
  * To improve accuracy   
    * Mesh refinement   
      * h-method, p-method  
      * Increase number of segments, increase polynomial order  
* Hermite Simpson Collocation  
  * Assume dynamics are quadratic between grid points   
  * State is a cubic spline  
  * Control and state at a midpoint of each interval   
  * Simpson Quadrature  
    * Hermite Interpolant   
    * Simpson Collocation  
* Collocation   
  *   
* Adaptive meshing   
  * Increasing the h and p methods at the least accurate segments   
* Hybrid systems  
  * Multi-phase trajectory optimization   
  * Through-contact trajectory optimization  
* Objective functions

Essentially converting a robotic task that consists of kinematic and dynamic parametrs of the robot, the goal of position velociy and duration and the given environment and formulate the problem into mathematical optimization problem for a NLP solver (or other solvers)

* Formulation of mathematical feasibility problem   
* Optimization over (constraints)  
  * CoM   
  * Base Orientation   
  * For every foot   
    * Foot position   
    * Foot force   
* Dynamic Model: Modeling the robot (to conform to physics)   
  * Single rigid body with mass (**m)** and 3 by 3 inertia matrix (**I)**  
  * The position of the rigid body is effected based on the feet   
    * Linear equation effect the mass   
    * Angular equation effect the inertia matrix   
    * Assumptions made  
      * Motion of the legs doesnt influence the base  
    * Allows for the formulation of equation fully in the cartesian space avoiding the joints non linearity relationshop   
* Kinematic Model  
  * Approximation of the joint limits

### Terminology 

Refs: [wiki](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trajectory_optimization)

* Decision variable  
  * Unknown found using optimization   
* Trajectory optimization problem  
  * Optimization problem where the decision variables are function  
* Parameter optimization  
  * Optimization problem where the decision variables are numbers  
* Nonlinear program  
  * Class of constrained parameter optimization where the objective function/constraints are nonlinear  
* Indirect method  
  * Analytically construct necessary and sufficient conditions for optimality   
  * Discretize the conditions constructing a constrained parameter optimization problem   
  * Solve that optimization problem  
* Direct method  
  * Discretize the problem directly converting it into constrained parameter optimization problem   
  * Solve that optimization problem   
* Transcription  
  * Trajectory optimization problem into parameter optimization problem (discretization)  
  * Shooting and collocation methods   
* Shooting method  
  * Based on simulation, using explicit Runge-Kutta schemes  
* Collocation method (Simultaneous Method)  
  * Based on function approximation, using implicit Runge-Kutta schemes  
* Pseudospectral method (Global Collocation)  
  * Transcription method that represents the entire trajectory as a single high order orthogonal polynomial  
* Mesh (Grid)  
* Mesh refinement  
* Multi-phase trajectory optimization problem

### An Introduction To Trajectory Optimization

Refs: [paper](https://epubs.siam.org/doi/pdf/10.1137/16M1062569)

* Trajectory described as a path that includes within it both state and control as functions of time.   
  * Where state might include position velocity and acceleration   
  * And control include things such as thrust   
* Trajectory optimization finds the best choice of trajectory by selecting the inputs into the system as a function of time.   
* Dynamics describe how the system moves   
* *Feasible trajectory* optimization problem is required to have a solution within the given problem constraints.   
  * Constraints can be system dynamics and the boundary conditions   
  * Set of control that produce feasible trajectories are known as *admissible controls*   
* Trajectory optimization tries to find the *optimal solution*  
  * Optimality is described by the mathematically formulated *objective function*  
* *Objective function* can include a boundary condition J(.) and path integral along the entire trajectory, with the path integrant w(.)  
  * Problem with both is *Bolza form* problem  
  * Problem with w(.) is *Lagrange form* problem  
  * Problem with J(.) is *Mayer form* problem

![][image1]  

* *Decision variables*  
  * The adjusted variables that minimize the objective function   
  * Some of the decision variables can be   
    * 0Initial and final time (t0  and tf )  
    * State trajectory x(t)  
    * Control trajectory u(t)  
* Multiple constraints go into optimization problem   
  * System dynamics   
    * Nonlinear(typically) and describe the system change in time   
    * ![][image2]  
  * Path constraints   
    * Enforce restriction along trajectory   
    * ![][image3]  
  * Boundary constraints   
    * Nonlinear in nature and put constraint on the initial and final states of the system   
    * ![][image4]  
  * State and control constraints   
    * The system most likely to have limits on the angle angular rate and torque that could be applied  
    * ![][image5]  
  * Initial and final state and time constraints   
    * Might help to insure the solution to a path planning problem reaching the goal within some time or region of space   
    * ![][image6]  
* *Direct Collocation Method*  
  * *Transcription*  
    * Direct methods discretize the trajectory optimization problem into a nonlinear program   
    * Continuous trajectory is discretized by approximating al the continuous function in the problem statement as polynomial splines   
      * Since polynomials   
        * Can be represented by finite set of coefficients   
        * Can easily compute integrals and derivatives in terms of these coefficients   
* *Nonlinear Programming*   
  * Constrained parameter optimization problem that has nonlinear terms in either it objective or its constraint function   
  * E.g. ![][image7]  
  * The nonlinear program is solved by a solvers   
  * In some cases the collocation method does yields a linear or quadratic program   
    * When the constraints are linear and the objective function is linear or quadratic resulting in corresponding linear or quadratic problem   
    * These problems are much easier to solve then the nonlinear programs  
* Block-Move Example   
  * Dynamics   
  * Boundary constraints   
  * Objective function  
    * Integral of control effort squared  
      * Tends to yield smooth solution trajectories  
    * ![][image8]  
  * Analytic Solution   
    * ![][image9]  
    * Found using *calculus of variations*   
      * Converting original problem into a system of differential equations that might (or might not) have an analytic solution   
    * *Indirect Methods* function in a similar way   
  * *Trapezoidal Collocation*  
    * Convert the original continuous-time problem \-\> nonlinear program   
    * Steps   
      * Discretize the trajectory, yielding a finite set of decision variables   
        * Represent x(t) and v(t) using *collocation points*   
          * Continuous function into specific points in time   
          * ![][image10]  
      * Derive the *collocation constraints*   
        * Convert continuous system dynamics into a set of constraints that can be applied to the state and control at the collocation points   
        * Using the trapezoidal quadrature/rule  
        * The idea is that the change between two collocation points is equal to the integral of the system dynamics   
        * The integral is represented using trapezoidal quadrature   
        * hk \= (tk-1 \- tk )  
        * ![][image11]  
          * This allows us to approximate the dynamics between each pair of collocation points   
        * These constraints are enforced on every segment of the trajectory   
          * ![][image12]  
      * The boundary conditions are added to the initial and final conditions   
        * ![][image13]  
      * Approximate the objective function using trapezoid quadrature   
        * Converting into summation over each segment   
        * Using control error at the collocation points   
        * ![][image14]  
    * *Initialization*  
      * For difficult problems good initial guess are import to allow convergence and optimality   
      * For this problem simple assumptions could be made   
        * Block transitions linearly   
        * Differentiating the initial position trajectory to compute the velocity and force trajectories   
        * ![][image15]	  
        * NOTE: The initial guess may violate some of the constraints   
      * Using initial trajectory evaluate it at each collocation point to obtain values to pass to the nonlinear programming solver  
        * ![][image16]  
    * *Nonlinear Program*   
      * Using direct transcription converts trajectory optimization problem into a nonlinear programming problem   
      * In this case its a quadratic program   
        * Constraints are linear and the objective function is quadratic   
    * *Interpolation*  
      * Solving the nonlinear program results in the set of positions, velocities and controls that satisfy the dynamic and boundary constraints and that minimize the objective function   
      * Using piecewise polynomial function (*spline)* that interpolates the solution trajectory between the collocation points   
      * For trapezoidal collocation use linear spline for the control and quadratic spline for the state   
  * *Trapezoidal Collocation Method*  
    * Trapezoidal collocation works by converting a continuous-time trajectory optimization problem into a nonlinear program   
      * Using trapezoidal quadrature for integration   
      * To convert each continuous aspect of the problem into a discrete approximation   
    * *Integrals*   
      * Integral expressions are found in the objective function sometimes in the constraints as well   
      * Goal is to approximate ![][image17] as a summation of  ![][image18]  
        * The summation requires the w(tk) evaluated for collocation points along the trajectory   
      * The approximation is done by applying the trapezoid rule for integration between each collocation point which yields   
      * ![][image19]  
      * Where hk \= tk=1 \- tk   
    * *System Dynamics*   
      * *Collocation constraints is a key feature*   
        * Direct collocation method represents the dynamics as a set of constraints   
      * Dynamics are written in integral form and then approximated using trapezoidal rule   
      * ![][image20]  
      * The approximation is applied between every pair of collocation points   
        * ![][image21]  
    * *Constraints*   
      * In addition to collocation constraints   
      * These are limits on state and control, path constraints, and boundary constraints   
      * These constraints are all handled by enforcing them at specific collocation points  
      * Path constraints tend to be much harder to solve  
      * In trapezoidal collocation the boundaries of the trajectory are always collocation points   
    * *Interpolation*   
      * *Linear splines* are used to approximate the control trajectory and the system dynamics   
      * *Knot point*   
        * Used to denote any point that joint two polynomial segments   
        * Constructing control trajectory   
          * Knowing time and control at each knot point   
          * Derive the expression for **u** on the interval t E\[tk, tk+1\]  
          * Using ![][image22] the control function   
            * ![][image23]
